      <controlProperties>
        <text>How%20does%20a%20distributed%20prize%20work%3F%20%20%0A%20%0AA%20traditional%20prize%20typically%20pays%20all%20of%20the%20money%20to%20the%20first%20person%20or%20team%20to%20meet%20the%20terms%20of%20the%20prize.%20%20For%20example%2C%20the%20Ansari%20X-prize%20paid%20%2410%20million%20to%20the%20winning%20SpaceShipOne%20team.%20%20The%20other%20teams%20received%20nothing%2C%20despite%20investing%20millions%20in%20their%20own%20efforts%20to%20win%20the%20prize.%20%20%0A%20%0AAs%20of%20a%20result%20of%20this%20%22winner%20takes%20all%22%20structure%2C%20traditional%20prizes%20have%20the%20disadvatage%20that%20the%20teams%20competing%20for%20the%20prize%20have%20little%20incentive%20to%20cooperate%20with%20each%20other.%20%20After%20all%2C%20if%20Team%20A%20shares%20information%20with%20Team%20B%2C%20and%20Team%20B%20meets%20the%20terms%20of%20the%20prize%20first%2C%20then%20Team%20B%20gets%20all%20the%20money%20and%20glory%2C%20and%20Team%20A%20gets%20nothing.%20%0A%20%0AThis%20is%20an%20especially%20important%20drawback%20when%20you%20want%20to%20incentivize%20a%20goal%20such%20as%20repealing%20pot%20prohibition.%20%20Repealing%20laws%20against%20pot%20use%20will%20require%20the%20efforts%20of%20a%20broadbased%20coalition%20of%20activists%2C%20legislators%2C%20and%20voters.%20%20Ideally%2C%20you%20would%20like%20everyone%20working%20together%20so%20that%20pot%20is%20legalized%20as%20quickly%20as%20possible.%20%0A%20%0ATypically%20speaking%2C%20the%20backers%20of%20a%20prize%20don%27t%20care%20who%20actually%20wins%20the%20prize.%20%20They%20only%20care%20that%20they%20get%20the%20results%20that%20they%20want.%20%20Therefore%2C%20why%20not%20set%20up%20the%20prize%20up%20in%20such%20a%20way%20to%20incentivize%20everyone%20working%20on%20the%20prize%20to%20cooperate%20with%20each%20other%3F%20%0A%20%0ADistributed%20prizes%20encourage%20cooperation%20amongst%20all%20of%20the%20people%20working%20to%20meet%20the%20terms%20of%20a%20prize.%20%0A%20%0AInstead%20of%20a%20single%20large%20prize%2C%20%20a%20distributed%20prize%20consists%20of%20many%20small%20prizes%2C%20each%20with%20the%20same%20terms.%20%20These%20prizes%20are%20created%20when%20someone%20puts%20up%20the%20money%20for%20the%20prize%20into%20an%20escrow%20account.%20%20This%20is%20called%20%22backing%20a%20prize%22.%20When%20a%20prize%20is%20first%20created%2C%20it%20is%20owned%20by%20the%20backer.%20%20The%20backer%20can%20then%20sell%20the%20prize%20at%20auction%20to%20the%20highest%20bidder.%20%20The%20high%20bidder%20then%20becomes%20the%20owner%20of%20the%20prize.%20%20If%20the%20terms%20of%20the%20prize%20are%20met%20before%20the%20deadline%2C%20then%20the%20funds%20are%20released%20from%20escrow%20and%20the%20owners%20of%20the%20prizes%20receive%20the%20face%20value%20of%20their%20prizes%20.%0A%20%0AFor%20example%2C%20suppose%20Sam%20is%20willing%20to%20pay%20%241000%20if%20pot%20is%20legalized%20at%20the%20federal%20level.%20%20%20He%20goes%20to%20potprize.com%20and%20transfers%20%241000%20into%20an%20escrow%20account.%20From%20the%20%241000%2C%20potprize.com%20creates%20ten%20%24100%20prizes%2C%20each%20with%20the%20same%20terms.%20%20Sam%20then%20auctions%20each%20prize%20off%20to%20the%20highest%20bidder.%20%20Suppose%20Bob%20is%20the%20high%20bidder%2C%20with%20a%20bid%20of%20%246.00%3B%20suppose%20he%20wants%20to%20buy%20seven%20prizes.%20%20He%20pays%20%2435.00%20to%20Sam%20%287%20x%20%246.00%29.%20%20Bob%20now%20owns%20six%20of%20Same%27s%20prizes.%20%20Let%27s%20assume%20that%20Hellen%20is%20the%20next%20highest%20bidder%20with%20a%20bid%20of%20%245.00%2C%20and%20she%20wants%20to%20buy%20three%20prizes.%20%20She%20pays%20%2415.00%20to%20Sam%20%283%20x%20%245.00%29.%20%20Helen%20now%20owns%20three%20of%20Sam%27s%20prizes.%20%20%0A%20%20%0ANow%2C%20suppose%20pot%20is%20legalized%20at%20the%20federal%20level%20%28as%20defined%20by%20the%20terms%20of%20the%20Pot%20Prize%20%29%20by%20midnight%20on%20January%201%2C%202015.%20%20The%20potprize.com%20pays%20Bob%20%24100%20for%20each%20of%20his%20prizes%2C%20for%20a%20total%20of%20%24700.00%20%287%20x%20%24100.00%29.%20%20The%20potprize.com%20pays%20Helen%20%24100%20for%20each%20of%20her%20prizes%2C%20for%20a%20total%20of%20%24300.00%20%283%20x%20%24100.00%29.%20%0A%20%0ABob%20has%20made%20%24665.00%20%28%24700.00%20-%20%2435.00%29.%20%20Helen%20has%20made%20%24285.00%20%28%24300.00%20-%20%2415.00%29.%20%20%28Ignore%20trading%20fees%20for%20the%20moment.%29%20%0A%20%0AOn%20the%20other%20hand%2C%20if%20the%20terms%20of%20the%20Pot%20Prize%20are%20not%20met%20by%20January%201%2C%202015%2C%20the%20prizes%20expire%2C%20and%20the%20money%20%28plus%20interest%29%20is%20returned%20to%20Sam%20and%20the%20other%20backers.%20%20%0A%20%0ABob%20and%20Helen%2C%20therefore%2C%20%20have%20strong%20incentives%20to%20actively%20work%20toward%20the%20legalization%20of%20pot.%20%20After%20all%2C%20if%20pot%20is%20not%20legalized%20by%20the%20deadline%2C%20then%20they%20will%20get%20nothing.%20%20They%20will%20have%20lost%20the%20money%20they%20paid%20for%20the%20prizes%20to%20begin%20with.%20%20They%20also%20have%20strong%20incentives%20to%20cooperate%20with%20each%20other--both%20will%20win%20money%20if%20pot%20is%20legalized.%20%20Similarly%2C%20everyone%20else%20who%20owns%20a%20pot%20prizes%20has%20an%20incentive%20to%20a%29%20work%20to%20meet%20the%20terms%20of%20the%20prize%0A%20and%20b%29%20cooperate%20with%20everyone%20else%20who%20owns%20a%20pot%20prize.%20%20%0A%20</text>
      </controlProperties>
    </control>
